content.text: JavaScript Data Types
JavaScript has 8 Datatypes
String Number Bigint Boolean Undefined Null Symbol Object
content.html:
String
Number
Bigint
Boolean
Undefined
Null
Symbol
Object

content.text: The Object Datatype
The object data type can contain both built-in objects , and user defined objects :
content.html: The object data type can contain both built-in objects, and user defined objects:

content.text: Built-in object types can be:
content.html: Built-in object types can be:

content.text: objects, arrays, dates, maps, sets, intarrays, floatarrays, promises, and more.
content.html: objects, arrays, dates, maps, sets, intarrays, floatarrays, promises, and more.

content.code_html:
// Numbers:
 let length = 16;
let weight = 7.5;

// Strings:
 let color = "Yellow";
let lastName = "Johnson";

// Booleans
 let x = true;
let y = false;

// Object:
 const person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe"};

// Array object:
 const cars = ["Saab", "Volvo", "BMW"];

// Date object:
 const date = new Date("2022-03-25");

content.text: Note
A JavaScript variable can hold any type of data.
content.html: A JavaScript variable can hold any type of data.

content.text: The Concept of Data Types
In programming, data types is an important concept.
content.html: In programming, data types is an important concept.

content.text: To be able to operate on variables, it is important to know something about the type.
content.html: To be able to operate on variables, it is important to know something about the type.

content.text: Without data types, a computer cannot safely solve this:
content.html: Without data types, a computer cannot safely solve this:

content.code: let x = 16 + "Volvo";
content.code_html: let x = 16 + "Volvo";

content.text: Does it make any sense to add "Volvo" to sixteen? Will it produce an error or will it produce a result?
content.html: Does it make any sense to add "Volvo" to sixteen? Will it produce an error or will it produce a result?

content.text: JavaScript will treat the example above as:
content.html: JavaScript will treat the example above as:

content.code: let x = "16" + "Volvo";
content.code_html: let x = "16" + "Volvo";

content.text: Note
When adding a number and a string, JavaScript will treat the number as a string.
content.html: When adding a number and a string, JavaScript will treat the number as a string.

content.code: let x = 16 + "Volvo";
content.code_html: let x = 16 + "Volvo";

content.code: let x = "Volvo" + 16;
content.code_html: let x = "Volvo" + 16;

content.text: JavaScript evaluates expressions from left to right. Different sequences can produce different results:
content.html: JavaScript evaluates expressions from left to right. Different sequences can produce different results:

content.code: let x = 16 + 4 + "Volvo";
content.code_html: let x = 16 + 4 + "Volvo";

content.code: let x = "Volvo" + 16 + 4;
content.code_html: let x = "Volvo" + 16 + 4;

content.text: In the first example, JavaScript treats 16 and 4 as numbers, until it reaches "Volvo".
content.html: In the first example, JavaScript treats 16 and 4 as numbers, until it reaches "Volvo".

content.text: In the second example, since the first operand is a string, all operands are treated as strings.
content.html: In the second example, since the first operand is a string, all operands are treated as strings.

content.text: JavaScript Types are Dynamic
JavaScript has dynamic types. This means that the same variable can be used to hold different data types:
content.html: JavaScript has dynamic types. This means that the same variable can be used to hold different data types:

syntaxHighlighting.text:
let x;       // Now x is undefined
x = 5;       // Now x is a Number
x = "John";  // Now x is a String

content.text: JavaScript Strings
A string (or a text string) is a series of characters like "John Doe".
content.html: A string (or a text string) is a series of characters like "John Doe".

content.text: Strings are written with quotes. You can use single or double quotes:
content.html: Strings are written with quotes. You can use single or double quotes:

content.code_html:
// Using double quotes:
 let carName1 = "Volvo XC60";

// Using single quotes:
 let carName2 = 'Volvo XC60';

content.text: You can use quotes inside a string, as long as they don't match the quotes surrounding the string:
content.html: You can use quotes inside a string, as long as they don't match the quotes surrounding the string:

content.code_html:
// Single quote inside double quotes:
 let answer1 = "It's alright";

// Single quotes inside double quotes:
 let answer2 = "He is called 'Johnny'";

// Double quotes inside single quotes:
 let answer3 = 'He is called "Johnny"';

content.text: You will learn more about strings later in this tutorial.
content.html: You will learn more about strings later in this tutorial.

content.text: JavaScript Numbers
All JavaScript numbers are stored as decimal numbers (floating point).
content.html: All JavaScript numbers are stored as decimal numbers (floating point).

content.text: Numbers can be written with, or without decimals:
content.html: Numbers can be written with, or without decimals:

content.code_html:
// With decimals:
 let x1 = 34.00;

// Without decimals:
 let x2 = 34;

content.text: Exponential Notation
Extra large or extra small numbers can be written with scientific (exponential) notation:
content.html: Extra large or extra small numbers can be written with scientific (exponential) notation:

content.code_html:
let y = 123e5;    // 12300000
 let z = 123e-5;   // 0.00123

content.text: Note
Most programming languages have many number types:
content.html: Most programming languages have many number types:

content.text: Whole numbers (integers): byte (8-bit), short (16-bit), int (32-bit), long (64-bit)
content.html:
Whole numbers (integers):
byte (8-bit), short (16-bit), int (32-bit), long (64-bit)

content.text: Real numbers (floating-point): float (32-bit), double (64-bit).
content.html:
Real numbers (floating-point):
float (32-bit), double (64-bit).

content.text: Javascript numbers are always one type: double (64-bit floating point).
content.html:
Javascript numbers are always one type:
double (64-bit floating point).

content.text: You will learn more about numbers later in this tutorial.
content.html: You will learn more about numbers later in this tutorial.

content.text: JavaScript BigInt
All JavaScript numbers are stored in a 64-bit floating-point format.
content.html: All JavaScript numbers are stored in a 64-bit floating-point format.

content.text: JavaScript BigInt is a new datatype ( ES2020 ) that can be used to store integer values that are too big to be represented by a normal JavaScript Number.
content.html: JavaScript BigInt is a new datatype (ES2020) that can be used to store integer values that are too big to be represented by a normal JavaScript Number.

content.code_html: let x = BigInt("123456789012345678901234567890");

content.text: You will learn more about BigInt later in this tutorial.
content.html: You will learn more about BigInt later in this tutorial.

content.text: JavaScript Booleans
Booleans can only have two values: true or false .
content.html: Booleans can only have two values: true or false.

content.code_html:
let x = 5;
let y = 5;
let z = 6;
(x == y)       // Returns true
(x == z)       // Returns false

content.text: Booleans are often used in conditional testing.
content.html: Booleans are often used in conditional testing.

content.text: You will learn more about booleans later in this tutorial.
content.html: You will learn more about booleans later in this tutorial.

content.text: JavaScript Arrays
JavaScript arrays are written with square brackets.
content.html: JavaScript arrays are written with square brackets.

content.text: Array items are separated by commas.
content.html: Array items are separated by commas.

content.text: The following code declares (creates) an array called cars , containing three items (car names):
content.html: The following code declares (creates) an array called cars, containing three items (car names):

content.code: const cars = ["Saab", "Volvo", "BMW"];
content.code_html: const cars = ["Saab", "Volvo", "BMW"];

content.text: Array indexes are zero-based, which means the first item is [0], second is [1], and so on.
content.html: Array indexes are zero-based, which means the first item is [0], second is [1], and so on.

content.text: You will learn more about arrays later in this tutorial.
content.html: You will learn more about arrays later in this tutorial.

content.text: JavaScript Objects
JavaScript objects are written with curly braces {} .
content.html: JavaScript objects are written with curly braces {}.

content.text: Object properties are written as name:value pairs, separated by commas.
content.html: Object properties are written as name:value pairs, separated by commas.

content.code: const person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe", age:50, eyeColor:"blue"};
content.code_html: const person = {firstName:"John", lastName:"Doe", age:50, eyeColor:"blue"};

content.text: The object (person) in the example above has 4 properties: firstName, lastName, age, and eyeColor.
content.html: The object (person) in the example above has 4 properties: firstName, lastName, age, and eyeColor.

content.text: You will learn more about objects later in this tutorial.
content.html: You will learn more about objects later in this tutorial.
